\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first thing we will prove is that congruence of triangles and similarity
 of triangles are both well defined equivalence relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Congruence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show congruence forms an equivalence relation, we need to show that congruenc
e of triangles is 
\series bold
i)
\series default
 Reflexive, 
\series bold
ii)
\series default
 Symmetric, 
\series bold
iii)
\series default
 Transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
i)
\series default
 Every triangle is congruent to itself, as every triangles will have the
 same side lengths and angles as itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
ii)
\series default
 Suppose triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is congruent to triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same side lengths and angles as 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the same side lengths and angles as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is also congruent to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
iii)
\series default
 Suppose triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is congruent to triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is congruent to triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 share the same side lengths and angles, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B,C$
\end_inset

 share the same side lengths and angles, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A,C$
\end_inset

 share the same side lengths and angles so 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are congruent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As all three properties are satisfied, then congruence of triangles is an
 equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show similarity forms an equivalence relation, we need to show that similarit
y of triangles is 
\series bold
i)
\series default
 Reflexive, 
\series bold
ii)
\series default
 Symmetric, 
\series bold
iii)
\series default
 Transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
i)
\series default
 Every triangle is similar to itself, as every triangles will have the same
 side lengths and angles as itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
ii)
\series default
 Suppose triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is similar to triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same angles as 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the same side lengths and angles as 
