\begin_layout Section*
Proofs of Congruence Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we will give a sketch of a proof for why the SSS, SAS, ASA rules work,
 as well as reasoning why ASS will not work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
SSS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law cosines states:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c^{2}=a^{2}+b^{2}-2ab\cos\left(C\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 are sides of the triangle, and C is the angle opposite side 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 As this is a triangle, we know 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\gamma<\pi$
\end_inset

, so we can uniquely determine 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 by solving the equation above for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\frac{\arccos\left(a^{2}+b^{2}-c^{2}\right)}{2ab}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As each angle can be found in the triangle by picking appropriate sides
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

, then we can determine the angles of both triangles only with information
 of the side lengths, thus both triangles sharing the same side lengths
 is sufficient to show that the two triangles are congruent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
SAS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, we can use the law of cosines.
 As the unknown side is the side opposite the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, then we simply solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 to find the missing side:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}-2ab\cos\left(C\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a triangle cannot have a negative side length, we can drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 sign when taking the square root.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 will have a unique value.
 Once we know all three side lengths we can rely on SSS to show both triangles
 are congruent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
ASA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time around, we will use the law of sines.
 Recall the law of sines:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{a}=\frac{\sin\left(B\right)}{b}=\frac{\sin\left(C\right)}{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, each side is denoted by a lower case 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 The angle opposite of a given side is given by taking a capital letter.
 Before we use the law of sines, let's first note the sum of the angles
 in a triangle will always be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 This means that given the two known angles, we can find the third angle
 by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi-A-B$
\end_inset

 (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are the known angles).
 Once we know three angles, and have one known side (suppose WLOG 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the known side), then we can solve for the remaining unknown sides as
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b=\frac{a\sin\left(B\right)}{\sin\left(A\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\frac{a\sin\left(C\right)}{\sin\left(A\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Why ASS fails
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we consider ASS, we do not have enough information to determine the missing
 side.
 Suppose WLOG the missing side is 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 If we try using the law of cosines, we can rearrange the equation to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=a^{2}-2ab\cos\left(C\right)+\left(b^{2}-c^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using quadratic formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\frac{2b\cos\left(C\right)\pm\sqrt{\left(-2b\cos\left(C\right)\right)^{2}-4\left(b^{2}-c^{2}\right)}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\frac{2b\cos\left(C\right)\pm\sqrt{4b^{2}\cos^{2}\left(C\right)-4\left(b^{2}-c^{2}\right)}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=b\cos\left(C\right)\pm\sqrt{b^{2}\cos^{2}\left(C\right)-b^{2}+c^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=b\cos\left(C\right)\pm\sqrt{b^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\left(C\right)-1\right)+c^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=b\cos\left(C\right)\pm\sqrt{b^{2}\left(-\sin^{2}\left(C\right)\right)+c^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have a valid triangle, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}\left(-\sin^{2}\left(C\right)\right)+c^{2}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 If it were not, we could not have a side length of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, as it would be imaginary.
 Further, we can assume that from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 we will only take the 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 If we have the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\cos\left(C\right)>\sqrt{b^{2}\left(-\sin^{2}\left(C\right)\right)+c^{2}}$
\end_inset

, then we may have two possible answers.
 Suppose we instead try using the law of sines:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{a}=\frac{\sin\left(B\right)}{b}=\frac{\sin\left(C\right)}{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
WLOG, we can try solving for an unknown angle.
 Suppose this angle is 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and we know the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\arcsin\left(\frac{b\sin\left(C\right)}{c}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we run into an issue.
 If we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin$
\end_inset

, we will get a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\pi}{2}<B<\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

, as the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The valid angles for a triangle lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 however.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin$
\end_inset

 will not be able to tell us if we have an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi-B$
\end_inset

, as these will yield the same result from 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin$
\end_inset

.
 As the law of cosines and law of sines both may yield two correct answers,
 ASS does not prove congruence of triangles in general.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Proofs of Similarity Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These similarity rules rely on the law of sines.
 Recall
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{a}=\frac{\sin\left(B\right)}{b}=\frac{\sin\left(C\right)}{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we rearrange the law of sines, we can show the following ratios hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{a}{b}=\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{\sin\left(B\right)},\frac{a}{c}=\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{\sin\left(C\right)},\frac{b}{c}=\frac{\sin\left(B\right)}{\sin\left(C\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this in mind, we can show why similarity holds for the following rules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
AA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we know two of the angles.
 Then we can find the third angle by subtracting the two known angles from
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose the first triangle have side lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and the second triangle has side lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $xa,xb,xc$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is some positive scaling factor.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{xa}{xb}=\frac{a}{b}=\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{\sin\left(B\right)},\frac{xa}{xc}=\frac{a}{c}=\frac{\sin\left(A\right)}{\sin\left(C\right)},\frac{xb}{xc}=\frac{b}{c}=\frac{\sin\left(B\right)}{\sin\left(C\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only way for all of the angles to be the same in each triangle is for
 the corresponding sides to be proportional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
SAS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we know two of the sides are proportional, and we know that the angle
 between the two sides, then we can show that the unknown side scales appropriat
ely using the law of cosines.
 Recall
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}-2ab\cos\left(C\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is opposite angle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, we will assume 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the unknown side.
 Suppose the first triangle have side lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and angle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and the second triangle has side lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $xa,xb$
\end_inset

 and angle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is some positive scaling factor.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\left(xa\right)^{2}+\left(xb\right)^{2}-2\left(xa\right)\left(xb\right)\cos\left(C\right)}=\sqrt{x^{2}a^{2}+x^{2}b^{2}-2x^{2}ab\cos\left(C\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=x\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}-2ab\cos\left(C\right)}=xc
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus all of the sides of triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 are proportional to those of triangle 1.
 As such, we can use the law of sines to solve for the remaining two angles
 for both triangles.
 These will both yield the same result as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{xa}{xc}\sin\left(C\right)=\frac{a}{c}\sin\left(C\right)=\sin\left(A\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{xb}{xc}\sin\left(C\right)=\frac{b}{c}\sin\left(C\right)=\sin\left(B\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and as we will know the ratios of the side lengths, we can be certain the
 law of sines is well defined, the only angle that can possibly be obtuse
 is an angle opposite of the longest side of the triangle.
 If we wait to solve for this angle until we know the other two angles,
 then we can take the difference of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and the two acute angles.
\end_layout

